TRIP COMMENTS: The following is based directly on my birding notes for this date and location; entered into eBird on 28 December, 2020.----Conducting monitoring for Metropolitan Water District of Southern California's Lake Mathews Shoreline Maintenance Project. This was during a time we (P&D Consutants) had a 2-year contract with the MWD, to assist them in monitoring (per their facility operations' permit conditions) the annual cutting of vegetation below the ordinary high-water mark at LM. This cutting was done during the non-breeding season (per permit regulations), and was performed by trained fire fighting crews that were inmates from the Norco and Bautista prisons in Riverside County. There would usually be one crew truck from each prison, with a fire captain with each truck overseeing the cutting. (No Correction officers present, as these were considered "low risk inmates", which were serving time for usually drug-related charges, and not "more serious" crimes, as we were told). The vegetation being cut was usually tamarisk (salt-cedar). They would allow the pre-existing mature native trees (primarily willows) to remain, although they'd cut saplings and the lower limbs of the mature trees. The primary purpose of this program was to eliminate or minimize potential nesting habitat for California Gnatcatchers and Bell's Vireos in the elevations that MWD could store water (brought in from the Colorado River Aquaduct I believe). The idea that removing potential breeding habitat for these birds, below the "ordinary high-water mark", would minimize the potential "take" of the two federally endangered/threatened species (if these species happened to have active nests in habitat that was to become inundated by water being pumped into LM).  It would normally take about four months to finish veg removal around the entire shoreline of LM. ----On this particular date we were working on the southwestern shoreline.  Weather was: "Partly cloudy through the morning overcast in the PM. ); 60s (deg. F), to 70sF." ----Abbreviations used:  LM = Lake Matthews; MWD = Metropolitan Water District of Southern California.
